ndigenous Peoples and Dementia responds to this call by bringing together, for the first time, research on three key areas of concern: prevalence, causes, and public discourse; Indigenous perspectives on care and prevention; and the culturally safe application of research to Elder care. The discussions are organized thematically and are complemented by teaching stories that impart Indigenous knowledge about memory loss and memory care. Presenting strategies for health practice and effective collaborative research informed by Indigenous knowledge and worldviews, this book is a valuable resource for researchers, practitioners, students, and educators who seek a better understanding of memory loss and memory care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDementiaxPatientsxCarexSocial aspects. 0aDementiaxPatientsxCare. 0aDementiaxPatients. 0aDementiaxPrevention. 0aIndigenous peoplesxHealth and hygiene. 0aOlder peoplexCare. 0aTraditional medicine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aBalestrery, Jean E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalestrery, Jean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlind, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourassa, Carrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell-McArthur, Gwen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarson, Linda D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeRose, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElder, Secwepemc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, J. Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulko, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g